annotation.TEXT: In the Twilight Zone episode “The Midnight Sun,” the Earth’s orbit has seemingly been disturbed, sending it closer to the sun and making temperatures soar.
The actual names of the lions used for the MGM mascot, in order of appearance, are Slats, Jackie, Telly, Coffee, Tanner, George, and Leo.
Kraft Music Hall was a radio and TV show that aired from 1933-71, hosted by Bing Crosby and Perry Como, among others. Both Liza Minnelli and Desi Arnaz Jr. appeared on the show.
The People’s Court is a daytime TV show originally featuring grumpy retired judge Joseph Wapner; it started the courtroom reality show craze.
Paraphrase of a line from the horror film A Nightmare on Elm Street.
Coney Island is in southern New York City, renowned for its amusement parks and hot dogs. Like most beaches, you can spot men with metal detectors patiently sweeping the sand for treasure.
Get the inside scoop behind every reference in this epic episode.
The first disc recording of the song was made in 1908.
Burma-Shave shaving cream was famous for its rhyming sequential road signs from the ‘20s-‘60s.
Humming the children’s song “The Teddy Bears’ Picnic.”
Mr. Goodwrench is the former name for GM’s auto repair division; Stephen Colbert played the character in a series of ads in 2003.
Cooky the Clown, played by Roy Brown, was Bozo the Clown’s sidekick for 25 years.
The phrase “crocodile tears” comes from a 14th-century tale that crocodiles weep either to lure their prey or as insincere repentance while eating them.
The American Humane Association holds a copyright on the famous movie credit line “No animals were harmed in the making of this film.”
The lisping Elmer Fudd first appeared in 1940, in the animated short Elmer’s Candid Camera. He has been voiced by 8 different actors, including Mel Blanc.
“Snack Canyon” refers to a series of movie theater promos for Coca-Cola products, popcorn, and candy that were used primarily in the late ‘70s.
Rhinelander is a city in northeast Wisconsin. It was originally called Pelican Rapids.
The famous weather folklore often attributed to sailors dates back thousands of years; Jesus even mentions it in the New Testament (Matthew 16:2b-3).
President Nixon’s “enemies list” was a list of 20 political opponents compiled by his aides; the official purpose of the list was to use the power of the presidency to harass them.
The seminal Woodstock Music & Art Fair, held in 1969, was billed as “3 Days of Peace & Music.” In fact it ended up lasting four days and attracted 400,000 people.
Host Red Skelton ended episodes on The Red Skelton Show by looking into the camera and saying, “Good night and may God bless.”
A take on the famous line “You’re gonna need a bigger boat. We’re gonna get a bigger boat, right?”, said by Roy Scheider after seeing the great white shark in Jaws.
The View-Master was created by a company called Sawyer’s in 1939. It was originally intended for people of all ages, but ended up as a children’s toy.
German dictator Adolf Hitler mostly rode around in massive Mercedes limousines; a number of the cars have survived in museums or private collections.
A paraphrase of a line from the Mae West film Every Day’s a Holiday: “You ought to get out of those wet clothes and into a dry martini.”
With annotations provided by The Annotated MST website.
The first actor to play Elmer Fudd was Arthur Q. Bryan, who also played Dr. Gamble on Fibber McGee and Molly.
Fibber McGee and Molly was a wildly popular radio show that aired on NBC from 1935-59.
“Shalom” is a Hebrew word that usually means “peace” but is used colloquially as both “hello” and “goodbye.”
Honey Nut Cheerios’ mascot has long been an anthropomorphized bee; after a contest in 2000, he was named BuzzBee, later shortened to Buzz.
A line from the 1939 film The Wizard of Oz.
Humming the theme song of the western movie High Noon.
Actor Tony Danza is best known for Taxi and Who’s the Boss?, though he’s gone on to star on a reality show where he taught school for a year and his own talk show.
Brought to you by the Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
Tradition says the annual running of the bulls in Pamplona began in the 1300s, as cattle herders would compete to see who could get their livestock to the market first.
This is the ad slogan for Quaker Oats’ breakfast cereal King Vitaman, first sold in 1968.
In 19th-century Cockney rhyming slang, “See you alligator” meant “See you later.” The more familiar phrase entered the mainstream in 1956 thanks to a Bill Haley and His Comets song by that title.
A progressive dinner (aka round-robin dinner or safari supper) is a kind of potluck event in which participants eat one course of an extensive meal at each host’s home.
“Mack the Knife” is a ballad about the highwayman Captain Macheath, from 1928’s The Threepenny Opera.
King Dinosaur: Fully annotated by The Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
Bless the Beasts and Children is a novel and film about a group of troubled boys who work together to stop a buffalo hunt. The film’s popular theme song was by The Carpenters.
A reference to MST3K Episode 208, Lost Continent.
Example: “A man -- A miss. A car -- A curve. He kissed the miss. And missed the curve. Burma-Shave.”
Another line from the 1939 film The Wizard of Oz.
A paraphrased line from the surrealist David Lynch TV series Twin Peaks: “The owls are not what they seem.”
“Please, get off the towers” was a warning given over the sound system at Woodstock by lighting designer Chip Monck as a storm began to come in.
Paraphrased lyrics from the song “The Unicorn,” written by Shel Silverstein and popularized by The Irish Rovers.
Contrary to popular belief, quicklime (aka calcium oxide) doesn’t hasten decomposition—in fact, it slows it, mummifying the corpse. It does reduce odors, though.
Legendary jazz musician Pete Fountain began playing the clarinet as a child because a doctor suggested it might help him strengthen his lungs after frequent respiratory infections.
In 1990, three pilots for Northwest Airlines were arrested for flying under the influence of alcohol; the captain reportedly had drunk 12-15 rum and diet colas before the flight.
The double entendre “Is that a ___ in your pocket or are you just happy to see me?” appears to have originated with Mae West, who claims she sassed some cops with it in the ‘30s.
The actual house filmed for exterior shots on The Brady Bunch is in Studio City, CA. The owners have extensively re-landscaped to make it less recognizable to fans.
Rock band Steely Dan got its name from a strap-on dildo mentioned in William Burroughs’ novel Naked Lunch.
Visa began in 1958 as a Bank of America pilot program and took the name Visa in 1976. MasterCard was known as Master Charge when it was founded in 1966.
Flamboyant pop singer Elton John has written a couple of songs about hell, including “My Kind of Hell”: “I can’t say I ever liked you much/But you’re my kind of hell.”
Midnight Express is a film about an American attempting to escape a Turkish prison. It was based on a nonfiction book by Billy Hayes and William Hoffer.
The phrase “Meanwhile, _____” originated with title cards in silent films. The phrase continued to be used by narrators of audio films and radio and TV shows.
Normally, vinyl replacement windows such as those manufactured by Andersen are filled with air or argon to help insulate the glass better.
Hawaii Five-O was a TV show about the exploits of a group of police detectives in Hawaii; it was remade in 2010. Why “Five-O”? Because Hawaii is the 50th state.
An impression of Laura Petrie, played by Mary Tyler Moore, on the classic CBS sitcom The Dick Van Dyke Show. Rob Petrie was played by Dick Van Dyke.
“Gertrude and Heathcliff, the Two Seagulls” was a recurring sketch on The Red Skelton Show. A young Johnny Carson wrote for the show, and these were among his favorite skits to write.
Teen heartthrobs Corey Haim and Corey Feldman were known as the Two Coreys; one of their films was License to Drive, in which they commit shenanigans in a vintage Cadillac.
“Neoconservatives” originally described right-leaning liberals; it has evolved to mean right-wingers who favor expanding democracy globally, even by force.
Comic character Little Orphan Annie’s other catchphrase, less well known, was “Gee whiskers!”
The original Bondo auto body filler was made of talc and plastic; before that, repairs were often made with highly toxic lead.
In 1983 the lyrics of the song were turned into an illustrated children’s book; the first printing came with a record of the song.
Mondo cane (Italian for A Dog’s World) is a 1962 documentary similar to a travelogue, but much of its content was chosen solely to shock and titillate.
Tarkus is the second album from the progressive rock group Emerson, Lake & Palmer. The cover features a large mechanized armadillo.
In Shakespeare’s tragedy Hamlet, the ghost of Hamlet’s father appears to demand that Hamlet avenge him. Tradition holds that he was first played by Shakespeare himself.
Producer Al Zimbalist also worked on Robot Monster (MST3K Episode 107). Donald Zimbalist was, in fact, his son.
The song has been recorded by Bing Crosby, The Nitty Gritty Dirt Band, Anne Murray, and others.
Thanks for watching this fully-annotated presentation of King Dinosaur.
Here Comes Mr. Jordan is a comedy about a boxer, sent to heaven before his time, who gets a second chance at life.
A paraphrase of “Seventy-Six Trombones,” a song from the 1957 musical/1962 film The Music Man.
Chocolate syrup, of various brands, was often used in place of blood in black-and-white films.
The myth of alligators living in NYC sewers began in 1935, when it was reported that a group of boys found and killed an 6-foot gator after a snowfall. It had probably escaped from a nearby ship.
This saying was first printed in a 1929 issue of Infantry Journal and was popularized in the 1951 Herman Wouk novel The Caine Mutiny.
“Fifteen men on the dead man’s chest” is the opening line from the pirate anthem “Dead Man’s Chest,” written by Robert Louis Stevenson for Treasure Island.
This is similar to the justifications given by supporters of the decision to use atomic bombs against Japan in WWII, who argue the Japanese had shown unyielding determination to continue fighting.
Actress Betty White has famously championed animal welfare causes since the 1970s.
Beany (a boy) and Cecil (a sea serpent) were originally puppets on the children’s TV show Time for Beany. They later starred in their own animated TV series.
A paraphrased line from the film It’s a Wonderful Life, spoken by Sheldon Leonard as Nick the bartender: “Get me! I’m givin’ out wings!” Hasidic Judaism is an orthodox branch of the faith.
James Dean had lead roles in only three films—Rebel Without a Cause, East of Eden, and Giant—before dying in a car crash at the age of 24.
Neil Armstrong may have bobbled his famous first words on the moon: that should be “One small step for a man.” There’s static on the recording, though, so he gets the benefit of the doubt.
Paraphrased lyrics from the song “Stranger in Paradise,” from the 1953 musical Kismet.
In Douglas Adams’ Hitchhiker’s Guide to the Galaxy books, two hyper-intelligent pan-dimensional beings are disguised as mice. Their names are Frankie and Benjy.
In wrestling, changing from a defensive position to controlling your opponent in one move is called a reversal—and it’s worth 2 points.
The end of the film The Fly finds the scientist played by David Hedison merged with a fly’s body and trapped in a spider web with the spider bearing down on him.
Mr. Moto, not “Dr.” (b. McRonald Kamaka), was a well-known pro wrestler in the ‘70s. He took his name from a fictional Japanese secret agent created by John P. Marquand.
It’s a Wonderful Life starred Jimmy Stewart as George Bailey, who famously learns what life would have been like had he never existed.
Jack Daniel’s whiskey (sometimes abbreviated as just “Jack” or “JD”) was first produced by distiller Jack Daniel in 1875.
The lines quoted here are from the title character’s famous soliloquy as he awaits battle with the English army, presented in Act V, Scene 5.
Crazy Guggenheim was the bug-eyed, hat-wearing drunk played by Frank Fontaine on The Jackie Gleason Show.
In 1988, at the Ramstein Air Base in West Germany, three jets collided in midair at an air show. One crashed into the audience; 70 people died and hundreds were injured.
“Teddy Bears’ Picnic” is a popular children’s song written by Jimmy Kennedy in 1932.
The opening dream sequence in Francis Ford Coppola’s Apocalypse Now features a montage of explosions and helicopters superimposed over Martin Sheen’s sleeping face.
Accessories made from alligator leather are extremely expensive due to the cost of the materials. It takes two alligators to make one purse, and it takes three years to raise them to a useful size.
“WASP,” as an acronym, means “White Anglo-Saxon Protestant.” The term was first published in 1957, although back then the W stood for “wealthy.”
Many German scientists surrendered to the US at the end of WWII; German war tech helped develop the Redstone rocket, which carried the Mercury astronauts into space.
A reference to the numbered joke scene in MST3K Episode 202, Sidehackers.
A famous line from the film The Elephant Man, from a scene in which the severely deformed John Merrick (based on the real-life Joseph Merrick) confronts an angry mob.
Getting paid scale refers to the minimum wage paid to actors for a day’s work. In the mid-’50s, that was less than $200.
Buckwheat was a character in the Our Gang/Little Rascals shorts with wild hair, bugged-out eyes, and odd speech inflections. He was famously parodied by Eddie Murphy on SNL.
Solarisation is a photographic effect that reverses the dark and light tones of a picture or negative.
A take on the 1950 song “Luck Be a Lady,” from the musical Guys and Dolls. Frank Sinatra famously performed it for many years.
Lake Mille Lacs is a lake north of Minneapolis known for its fishing; Uncle Josh is a bait and lure company founded in 1922 Wisconsin. The pork rinds are bait for larger fish, BTW.
The Satan riff was frequently used on MST3K when there was a snake on screen.
Wally Karbo was a pro wrestling promoter in Minneapolis, co-founder of the American Wrestling Association, and host of the Saturday morning AWA show All-Star Wrestling.
No rockets have ever been launched from the Eiffel Tower, but people have bungee jumped from it, flown planes under it (1926, unsuccessfully; 1984, successfully), and parachuted from it. (Bad idea.)
Psychotronic Video was a film magazine from 1980-2006. A book version was first published in 1983: The Psychotronic Encyclopedia of Film. It focused on sci-fi, horror, exploitation, etc.
A line from MST3K Episode 207, Wild Rebels.
This proverb dates to the 15th century.
Northern pike are a large, carnivorous freshwater fish sometimes called jackfish. The hula popper is a type of fishing lure used to catch them.
A Pampers ad campaign in the ‘80s expressed sympathy for any baby stuck in “a saggy diaper that leaks.”
“Nyuk, nyuk, nyuk” was one of Curly Howard’s (aka Jerome Horwitz) trademark vocalizations in the Three Stooges shorts.
A mashup of two famous JFK quotations, one from a 1961 speech before a joint session of Congress, and the second from his inaugural address earlier in the year.
When the cardinals meet to elect a new pope, they burn the ballots in a stove in the Sistine Chapel. Black smoke from the chimney means no pope has been chosen. White smoke means one has.
“Jimmyhat” or “jimmy hat” is a slang term for a condom.
Dean died outside Paso Robles, CA, when his Porsche crashed into a car turning ahead of him.
Big Ben is actually the name of the largest bell in the clock tower of the Palace of Westminster in London, but most people use it to refer to the clock as well.
The Precambrian time, which is not truly an era or eon, began with the formation of the Earth 4.6 billion years ago and ended 540 million years ago.
On one of the recordings of President Nixon and his Watergate co-conspirators there is an 18-minute gap, implausibly attributed to his secretary’s accidental erasure.
Raymond Carver was a short story writer and poet who became highly acclaimed in the ‘80s for his minimalist stories.
“One-third less calories than our regular beer” was a selling point for Miller Lite.
In a popular episode of the classic British sitcom Fawlty Towers, a guest annoys Basil (John Cleese) by ordering a Waldorf salad even though it is not on the menu.
The film A Guy Named Joe and its remake Always are about a ghostly pilot who mentors a younger pilot as he falls in love with the dead guy’s gal.
The American Gladiators TV show featured amateur athletes competing against oiled-up wrestler types with names like Turbo and Nitro.
“Fahrvergnügen” is a German neologism meaning “driving pleasure,” which Volkswagen used as an ad slogan from 1990-92.
Legendary crooner and actor Frank Sinatra was allegedly linked to numerous mafia figures, including Sam Giancana and Bugsy Siegel.
The phrase “a penny for your thoughts” is a very old one, first published in a collection of proverbs by playwright John Heywood in 1546. (He didn’t coin the proverbs; he just compiled them.)
In 1964 President Lyndon Johnson sparked a national outrage when he was photographed lifting one of his beagles partway off the ground by his ears.
“The Maidenform woman. You never know where she’ll turn up” was the tagline for a series of ads for Maidenform bras during the ‘70s & ‘80s.
In Monty Python and the Holy Grail, Dennis the Peasant takes offense at being called “old woman,” pointing out, first, that he’s a man, and second, “I’m thirty-seven. I’m not old.”
There is a famous variety of marijuana called Pinky Stinky, as well as countless other variants such as Black Diesel and Black Jack, but we couldn’t find one called Pinky Black.
A reference to yet another Lippert film: MST3K Episode 203, Jungle Goddess.
An exchange from the Marx Brothers movie A Day at the Races, between Gil (played by Allan Jones) and Groucho.
Executive producer Robert Lippert also produced other films riffed on by MST3K, including Episode 520, Radar Secret Service, and Episode 611, Last of the Wild Horses.
A paraphrased line from the film Planet of the Apes: “Take your stinking paws off me, you damned dirty ape!”
In ads for the OTC pain reliever Excedrin dating back to the ‘70s, sufferers would say, “I’ve got a headache this big, and it’s got Excedrin written all over it.”
The Marquess of Queensberry rules for boxing were not written by him, but he was a keen boxing fan and a major supporter of the sport, so they were named after him.
“I’m huge!” is a long-running riff on MST3K; the phrase originally came from the comic Jimbo: Adventures in Paradise, by Pee-wee’s Playhouse set designer Gary Panter.
It’s actually a kinkajou.
“Pattycake” (aka “Pat-a-cake”) is a nursery rhyme that dates back to the 1600s and is usually accompanied by a clapping game.
Mr. Do-Bee and Mr. Don’t-Bee taught safety habits on the kids’ TV show Romper Room.
“Hello, Joe. What do you know?” was a greeting popularized by vaudeville routines and the song “Well All Right (Tonight’s the Night),” performed by The Andrews Sisters, Ella Fitzgerald, and more.
A reference to the famous scene in the film Alien in which the titular character first appears. If you haven’t seen it, it’s known as the “chestburster,” which should give you some idea.
“Wildwood Weed” is a song recorded by Jim Stafford (of Riding with Death fame) in 1974. It’s about marijuana.
“Eighty-six” as slang meaning to get rid of something/someone is believed to have originated in the ‘30s as restaurant code for “we’re out of it.”
Braille was invented in 1821 by Louis Braille, a blind French musician and teacher.
In 1966, Charles Whitman climbed the tower of the University of Texas’ main building and opened fire. 14 died and 32 were wounded before police killed him two hours later.
“Cheese it!” meaning “be quiet” or “stop it,” first appeared in published form in O. Henry’s 1908 book The Voice of the City, but it was being used in the 1800s in the UK.
The first CD ever sold in stores was Billy Joel’s album 52nd Street. At that time, in 1982, the discs cost $30 or more and the players went for $900.
In 1977 an album was released taken from bootleg recordings: Live! at the Star-Club in Hamburg, Germany; 1962. The Beatles sued to block the release but lost the case.
An imitation of child actor Clint Howard (Ron Howard’s brother) on the TV show Gentle Ben.
In the novel Flowers for Algernon and its film adaptation Charly, Algernon is a lab mouse who undergoes an experiment to increase his intelligence.
Ed Herlihy was a TV and radio announcer known to most as the voice of Kraft ads from the ‘40s to the ‘80s.
The real John “Grizzly” Adams died from a head wound he got wrestling a bear; it kept getting reopened, leaving his brain exposed, and a monkey finally bit him there. He died four months later.
Actress/sex symbol Jayne Mansfield was killed instantly when her car drove into and underneath a tractor trailer.
Led Zeppelin’s “Stairway to Heaven” has been performed at nearly all of their concerts since April 1971, except when cut short for technical glitches or curfews.
Islamic tradition also holds that Satan was the serpent who tempted Adam and Eve, although he is sometimes identified as a Jinn rather than a fallen angel.
Where the Boys Are is a 1960 film about four coeds who travel to Fort Lauderdale on spring break in search of fun and men.
Let us know if we missed any references!
The American Tourister suitcase company ran those memorable ads showing a gorilla mistreating their luggage, though for some reason people always think that was Samsonite.
I’m OK, You’re OK is a 1969 self-help book by Dr. Thomas Harris, one of the best-selling self-help books ever published.
A 1932 recording of the song by Henry Hall and His Orchestra was used for decades to calibrate BBC audio equipment.
While Satan is most often described as a “fallen angel,” his initial job seems to have been as a prosecutor of sorts, to test men’s faith.
“Teddy Bears’ Picnic” used the tune of a song written by John Walter Bratton in 1907.
Ivan Tors was a Hungarian writer/producer who produced Gentle Ben, Sea Hunt, and Clarence the Cross-Eyed Lion, among others.
A line from another Lippert film: MST3K Episode 201, Rocketship X-M.
The opening credits of the TV show Petticoat Junction showed three young comely lasses—and their dog—popping their heads up over the edge of a water tank.
Bryan was the definitive Fudd; Blanc admitted that after Bryan died, he never quite got the voice right.
For a mere $261K, you can own the Diamond Forever bag by Chanel, made from white alligator skin, 334 diamonds, and 18-karat gold hardware.
“Rhubarb” is one of the words background extras are told to mutter to simulate conversation in TV shows and films.
Dancer Isadora Duncan died when her long scarf tangled in one of her car’s wheels and broke her neck.
Weber is a brand of backyard grills; the rounded shape of their classic charcoal grill is iconic.
A 1981 Richard Avedon photo of actress Nastassja Kinski draped in a large boa constrictor and nothing else became a popular poster.
And now, we invite you to enjoy…the fully-annotated King Dinosaur!
An imitation of Groucho Marx in the Marx Brothers movie Animal Crackers.
Dunkirk is a coastal city in France, famous for the evacuation of more than 338,000 Allied soldiers in just 9 days by 850 British boats as France fell to the Nazis in 1940.
Bert I. Gordon is a director and producer known for featuring supersized animals and people in his films—hence his nickname, “Mister B.I.G.”
“Laugh, and the world laughs with you/Weep, and you weep alone” is from the 1883 poem “Solitude” by Ella Wheeler Wilcox.
The morning zoo radio format was invented by two Tampa DJs in the early ‘80s; one of them took the format to Z-100 in NYC and dubbed it the Morning Zoo; her success was swiftly copied nationwide.
Things don’t end well for the spider or the fly.
Did we somehow miss a reference? Let us know in the comments!
Jack Daniel’s is the best-selling American whiskey in the world.
The most famous Gorgon was Medusa, but there were two more, Stheno and Euryale. It’s possible they meant Gorgo, a British Godzilla movie given the MST3K treatment in Episode 909.
The title characters on the show were played by real-life couple Jim and Marian Jordan.
August Strindberg was an influential Swedish playwright and novelist. This may be a reference to The Lamb and the Beast, a play Strindberg wrote about Jesus.
Despite the name, Greco-Roman wrestling was neither. It was French, first exhibited by a Napoleonic soldier, and was dubbed “Greco-Roman” because supporters felt it represented ancient values.
Did we miss any references? Be sure to let us know in the comments!
These days, Rolling Stones guitarist Keith Richards is a frighteningly gaunt man who has somehow survived decades of heavy substance abuse.
Paraphrase of a line from the horror film A Nightmare on Elm Street.
“Hurts, don’t it?” is a line from the Patrick Swayze film Road House.
Necco Wafers come in eight flavors: lemon, lime, orange, clove, cinnamon, wintergreen, licorice, and chocolate.
The game of bingo was invented only in the 1920s, although it was based on an 18th-century French game called Le Lotto. It was originally called “Beano.”
A mid-‘60s ad jingle, sung by Barry Manilow, for the Polaroid Swinger, an instant camera that flashed the word “YES” in the viewfinder when the shot was in focus.
Blood Alley is an adventure film starring John Wayne as a Merchant Marine captain involved in derring-do in China.
The ‘70s TV cop show Starsky & Hutch featured lots of stunt driving in the title duo’s red and white Gran Torino, which became increasingly battered over the course of the show.
Miller’s Crossing is a black comedy about a war between rival gangsters in the ‘30s. It was made by brothers Joel and Ethan Coen, known for Raising Arizona, Fargo, and more.
Hunky leading man Patrick Swayze’s dad, Jesse Swayze, was an engineering draftsman.
Beginning in the ‘70s, audiences began to call out requests for the Lynyrd Skynyrd song “Free Bird” at concerts by any performers, regardless of genre.
In his 1982 song “Dirty Laundry,” Don Henley sings about a “bubble-headed bleached blonde who comes on at five.”
A riff on a scene in the movie Monty Python and the Holy Grail.
The Chain of Lakes is a district in Minneapolis: an ancient Mississippi River channel that is now a string of five interconnected lakes.
This is how Jerry Mathers was introduced in the opening credits of Leave It to Beaver. George Mathews (the guardian angel) was a character actor who mostly played tough guys on TV.
Named after the TV detective show The Rockford Files, a Rockford turn is a stunt-driving maneuver: a 180-degree spin while racing forward.
Scope mouthwash ads in the late ‘70s showed a married couple waking up and quickly turning away from each other while the narrator intoned, “They wake with the worst breath of the day.”
Although the serpent in the Garden of Eden has traditionally been regarded as a personification of Satan, it is never explicitly named as such in Genesis.
A paraphrase of the final line in the film King Kong (both the 1933 and 2005 versions): “It wasn’t the airplanes. It was beauty killed the beast.”
Nixon and his aides also swore often, which was rendered on the transcripts as “Expletive deleted.” At the height of the scandal, Nixon famously declared at a press conference, “I am not a crook.”
While there have been many clowns who have gone by “Cooky” or “Cookie,” the most famous is Cooky the Cook, Bozo’s sidekick on WGN’s Bozo’s Circus.
An imitation of the pirate Long John Silver in Treasure Island; “Jim boy” is the protagonist, Jim Hawkins.
A line from the Hank Williams song “Jambalaya (On the Bayou).”
The stinger of a famous campfire tale wherein a hook-handed man terrorizes teens making out in cars.
Gino Vannelli is a curly-haired Canadian singer/songwriter whose hits include “People Gotta Move” and “I Just Wanna Stop.”
The short-lived documentary TV series Living Dangerously first aired in 1986.
“Run Through the Jungle” is a song by Creedence Clearwater Revival. Songwriter John Fogerty has said it is about the proliferation of guns in the US.
Judy “Dorothy Gale” Garland struggled with addictions to alcohol and barbiturates throughout most of her career; she died from an accidental overdose of barbiturates.
The Rolling Stones’ “Get Off of My Cloud” was a reaction to the demands that followed their mega-hit “Satisfaction.”
The half-Vulcan Mr. Spock was originally going to be half-Martian; it was changed because Star Trek creator Gene Roddenberry thought humans might go to Mars during the series’ run.
The Exxon Valdez spilled millions of gallons of oil into Prince William Sound in 1989, killing hundreds of thousands of animals and costing more than $2 billion to clean up.
Of the dozens of brands under the Kraft Foods umbrella, 40 of them are more than a century old.
